WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:18.740
Alright, thank you for all, thank you everyone for being here, the last talk.

00:00:18.740 --> 00:00:25.360
Thank you to everyone at RStudio for putting on this great conference and for inviting

00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:34.580
me to give this talk which will be a bit of a change of pace as I am much more of a historian

00:00:34.580 --> 00:00:36.299
than a programmer.

00:00:36.299 --> 00:00:43.099
So my name is Jesse Sadler and I'm currently a lecturer at Loyola Marymount University

00:00:43.099 --> 00:00:46.180
in Los Angeles.

00:00:46.180 --> 00:00:52.459
And today, instead of going into some technical details about TidyEval, though I have used

00:00:52.459 --> 00:01:01.540
TidyEval, I am going to talk about how the tidyverse helped me to learn to code and then

00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:09.860
it helped me to learn to create something to make a package that solved a problem that

00:01:09.860 --> 00:01:13.660
I had long had as a researcher in history.

00:01:13.660 --> 00:01:18.400
Okay, so what do I do?

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:26.900
As a historian, my research is based around studying sibling relationships and inheritance

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:31.959
in early modern Europe and in the development of early modern capitalism.

00:01:31.959 --> 00:01:42.639
Specifically, I look at two merchant families from Antwerp and their social relationships,

00:01:42.639 --> 00:01:47.320
the sibling relationships and their inheritance.

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:48.680
So what does that mean?

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:56.040
Basically, I spend a lot of my time reading letters from the 16th century, reading letters,

00:01:56.040 --> 00:02:04.080
lawsuits that were made between family members especially, testaments and account books.

00:02:04.080 --> 00:02:09.520
And so I do this in archives in the Netherlands and Belgium.

00:02:09.520 --> 00:02:14.479
There's even an archive that I work on that's in a castle in Belgium.

00:02:14.479 --> 00:02:18.080
So that's fun.

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:31.240
So I had long been interested in learning to code or to do something with what we call

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:34.520
in humanities, digital humanities.

00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:40.080
And I had been interested in this, but I didn't know where to start.

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:45.440
The power of coding from the outside was very alluring.

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:49.759
So maybe some of you remember this, maybe some of you don't.

00:02:49.759 --> 00:02:59.240
But if you don't know what it is, it's exciting, but you have no idea what it could be.

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:05.639
As I learned more about it, I was interested in the ability to build something that was

00:03:05.639 --> 00:03:09.919
set up exactly for what I wanted to do.

00:03:10.759 --> 00:03:12.960
I had used spreadsheets.

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:19.399
I was very much interested in the separation of data entry, because I have to enter most

00:03:19.399 --> 00:03:23.000
of my own data from the archives.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:31.160
And separating that from data analysis, as Jenny Bryan has talked about a lot.

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:36.199
And so I was interested in it, but I didn't know what to do.

00:03:36.199 --> 00:03:43.279
And a lot of what people say when people come up and they say, oh, I want to learn

00:03:43.279 --> 00:03:44.279
to code.

00:03:44.279 --> 00:03:46.000
They say, OK, well, pick a project.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:49.600
Well, I didn't know what a project was.

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:54.960
OK, I'll pick a project.

00:03:54.960 --> 00:03:57.759
What's a project?

00:03:57.759 --> 00:04:01.119
What programming language am I going to need?

00:04:01.119 --> 00:04:02.759
What do I even need?

00:04:02.759 --> 00:04:04.639
I don't know what I need.

00:04:04.639 --> 00:04:16.200
So this really kind of kept me for a long time in trying to take what I knew from history,

00:04:16.200 --> 00:04:18.519
from the humanities, and learning a whole new skill.

00:04:18.519 --> 00:04:21.959
I didn't really know what to do.

00:04:21.959 --> 00:04:30.440
And so I think that the Tidy Tuesday whole project is really interesting in this regard,

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:35.640
because it demonstrates, OK, here's something that you can do.

00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:40.519
And it's manageable, and it's reasonable, and you can get it.

00:04:40.519 --> 00:04:44.279
But I didn't know that.

00:04:44.279 --> 00:04:52.640
So I said, OK, I'm going to, after a long period of not doing anything, I said, OK,

00:04:52.640 --> 00:05:00.519
I'm going to actually put my foot down and learn this whole digital thing.

00:05:00.519 --> 00:05:05.760
So I said, OK, I think I have a project that would be a project.

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:14.880
I have in the archives 6,000 letters, or over 6,000 letters, that were sent to a merchant,

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:22.640
Daniel von der Molen, over a period of 22 years, from 1578 to 1600.

00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:28.640
And I said, OK, I could probably map these.

00:05:28.640 --> 00:05:34.720
And so I hem and hawed, and I thought about, OK, is there a GUI application that I could

00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:36.880
just put some data in and get something out?

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:43.119
And I said, no, I'm going to learn how to do it by myself.

00:05:43.119 --> 00:05:48.760
I had some help from a friend, and I looked around, and I said, OK, why not this whole

00:05:48.760 --> 00:05:51.079
R thing?

00:05:51.079 --> 00:06:00.000
So how, then, did I learn how to program in R?

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:06.880
Basically, well, how did I learn how to program in R, and how did the tidyverse help me?

00:06:06.880 --> 00:06:08.959
That's my talk.

00:06:08.959 --> 00:06:15.160
So the short story is that I basically just read Gerrit Grohlmann's and Hadley Wickham's

00:06:15.160 --> 00:06:16.279
R for data science.

00:06:16.279 --> 00:06:23.200
I sat there, and I had it pinned to my browser, and I would read a chapter, and I would take

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:28.519
notes, and then I would read it again.

00:06:28.519 --> 00:06:32.839
And so that's pretty much how I learned.

00:06:32.839 --> 00:06:40.700
But there's a lot of sophisticated arguments about nonstandard evaluation and whether the

00:06:40.700 --> 00:06:46.040
syntax in tidyverse is better than it is in base R and all those things, and I'm not going

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:51.720
to talk about that, because as a beginner, it didn't really matter to me which way was

00:06:51.720 --> 00:06:54.000
better.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:58.359
It just mattered that there was a way.

00:06:58.359 --> 00:07:03.519
And tidyverse, I think, really helped me in that it was nice and bounded, and you could

00:07:03.519 --> 00:07:06.880
do things with it, but it was also limited.

00:07:06.880 --> 00:07:13.239
Yes, dplyr is a huge package, but you don't need to know at least at the beginning about

00:07:13.239 --> 00:07:15.600
most of dplyr.

00:07:15.600 --> 00:07:20.079
So I really enjoyed the bounded nature of it.

00:07:20.079 --> 00:07:28.559
You read in data with read R, you do something with it with dplyr, and then you visualize

00:07:28.559 --> 00:07:32.839
it with ggplot, and you're like, yes, I have something.

00:07:32.839 --> 00:07:41.519
So that ability, it showed me that, okay, one, I can learn to do this, so that's good,

00:07:41.519 --> 00:07:52.559
but two, that it would be valuable for me to put in the effort to learn how to do this.

00:07:52.559 --> 00:08:03.880
So what really scared me, I think, at the beginning of learning to code in R was one

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:06.959
of the things that makes R great, which is all the packages.

00:08:06.959 --> 00:08:10.839
There's so many different ways to do all these different things.

00:08:10.839 --> 00:08:15.359
But I was not interested in that.

00:08:15.359 --> 00:08:24.040
And so at the beginning, what I really was doing was I took solace in library tidyverse

00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:31.880
and just typed that in, and then know that everything will be okay.

00:08:31.880 --> 00:08:39.400
And so here I really have to thank the entire R community, R studio community, tidyverse

00:08:39.400 --> 00:08:47.440
community for helping me learn, for all the great resources that there are, for keeping

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:50.400
me excited about learning more.

00:08:50.400 --> 00:09:00.159
I started a blog where I went through sort of my learning process at jessysadler.com,

00:09:00.159 --> 00:09:07.679
and the response that I've gotten from that sort of has been way larger than I would have

00:09:07.679 --> 00:09:10.400
ever expected.

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:16.280
In the first project that I was working on, the SF package came out, right, or was really

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:18.419
getting going right as I was doing that.

00:09:18.419 --> 00:09:19.419
So it was great.

00:09:19.419 --> 00:09:26.280
I really had fun delving into SF and into GIS.

00:09:26.280 --> 00:09:31.479
And so far, I have a map of letters up to 1591.

00:09:31.479 --> 00:09:33.159
It's not the code that's holding me back.

00:09:33.159 --> 00:09:37.640
It's going through and cataloging all those letters.

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:42.599
Which is a little bit more� when you have to actually input your own data, the coding

00:09:42.599 --> 00:09:43.599
seems easier.

00:09:43.599 --> 00:09:46.520
At least it takes less time.

00:09:46.960 --> 00:09:47.960
Okay.

00:09:47.960 --> 00:09:56.960
So what I want to do for the rest of the talk is to discuss a new project that I've been

00:09:56.960 --> 00:10:03.440
working on, a package that I have built that deals specifically with a historic issue.

00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:13.520
And so we're really going down to narrow use case, but hopefully you'll bear with me here.

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:20.119
So the package that I have developed, I've called DebKeeper, which is short for Double

00:10:20.119 --> 00:10:29.640
Entry Bookkeeping, or Double Entry Bookkeeper, which I know sounds amazing already.

00:10:29.640 --> 00:10:34.520
So this is on GitHub right now.

00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:40.880
But the package is basically� there's more I want to do with it, but it's basically ready.

00:10:40.880 --> 00:10:49.520
And it has a package down website with three vignettes and descriptions of how to do things.

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:50.520
Okay.

00:10:50.520 --> 00:10:56.760
So let me start� before I get into what that is, let me discuss what the historical

00:10:56.760 --> 00:10:59.479
issue that I was seeking to solve is.

00:10:59.479 --> 00:11:02.119
So I'm interested in the history of accounting.

00:11:02.119 --> 00:11:05.400
And that might not sound that interesting.

00:11:05.400 --> 00:11:06.559
Or you may be an accountant.

00:11:06.559 --> 00:11:07.559
I don't know.

00:11:07.559 --> 00:11:13.479
But the reason I'm interested in the history of accounting is because accounting deals

00:11:13.479 --> 00:11:15.760
with social relationships.

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:19.599
It's not the accounting part, it's the social relationships.

00:11:19.599 --> 00:11:26.159
And why accounting is particularly interesting for me, in my context, is that in the early

00:11:26.159 --> 00:11:31.520
modern period, in most of the low countries where I do my work, inheritance was perfectly

00:11:32.520 --> 00:11:41.599
Meaning that all male and female heirs received the exact same amount of inheritance.

00:11:41.599 --> 00:11:45.880
And when you're dealing with merchant families, that means accounting has to go into figuring

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:52.159
out how much the estate is worth and then how much each individual person gets.

00:11:52.159 --> 00:11:56.280
And it has to be exactly right.

00:11:56.280 --> 00:12:03.679
So and here you can see a document where it's doing that.

00:12:03.679 --> 00:12:08.440
So merchant families inheritance involves accounting.

00:12:08.440 --> 00:12:14.960
Now one problem with that, other than it's accounting, is that the currency that they

00:12:14.960 --> 00:12:25.200
use, as you can see on the right, is essentially pounds, shillings, and pence.

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:32.440
One pound, if you can't remember before pre-decimalization, equals 20 shillings.

00:12:32.440 --> 00:12:37.719
One shilling is equal to 12 pence.

00:12:37.719 --> 00:12:44.599
So this creates a number of problems because it's not decimal.

00:12:44.599 --> 00:12:48.880
Firstly, arithmetic calculations are cumbersome.

00:12:48.880 --> 00:12:55.239
I never thought I would be doing so much arithmetic as a historian.

00:12:55.239 --> 00:12:59.559
So I have pages and pages of just doing handwritten arithmetic.

00:12:59.559 --> 00:13:07.000
It's not hard, but more importantly, probably, is how to deal with tripartite non-decimal

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.239
values in a database.

00:13:10.239 --> 00:13:15.400
And so this has the same issues if you're going to try and think about it in R or any

00:13:15.400 --> 00:13:16.400
computer.

00:13:16.400 --> 00:13:18.679
Computers are decimal.

00:13:19.479 --> 00:13:24.280
Firstly, you have three separate units to make up one value.

00:13:24.280 --> 00:13:32.599
The units have non-decimal bases, and to make things worse, the bases can be different.

00:13:32.599 --> 00:13:39.840
So 20 and 12 is the most usual, but there's also 20 and 16, and there's 60 and 12, and

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:42.599
all sorts of different things.

00:13:42.599 --> 00:13:48.320
So how did I get over this?

00:13:48.320 --> 00:13:55.479
In the DebKeeper package, I created a class that I call LSD, which comes from the Latin

00:13:55.479 --> 00:14:00.119
names for pounds, shillings, and pence, Libra, Solidus, and Denarius.

00:14:00.119 --> 00:14:04.119
So you're getting some Latin in here.

00:14:04.119 --> 00:14:05.880
So what does it do?

00:14:05.880 --> 00:14:13.280
Basically, it makes these values a numeric vector of length three.

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:18.919
It also has a bases attribute that keeps track of what the bases for the shillings

00:14:18.919 --> 00:14:28.159
and pence are, and then they are stored as lists so that you can use them as a list column

00:14:28.159 --> 00:14:31.159
and you can have multiple in one object.

00:14:31.159 --> 00:14:40.559
So this is basically what it looks like here from a vector, Deb as LSD, Deb as in double-entry

00:14:40.559 --> 00:14:51.080
bookkeeping, and then you can also input these values as separate columns in a spreadsheet

00:14:51.080 --> 00:15:01.840
or something, a CSV, and then bring them together with a function called Deb LSD gather.

00:15:01.840 --> 00:15:09.400
So the coolest thing that I first started off with, and you might not think this is

00:15:09.400 --> 00:15:17.320
cool, but it was really cool to me, one might say magical, was that I could normalize the

00:15:17.320 --> 00:15:18.320
values.

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:23.159
So I could add up pounds, add up shillings, add up pence, and then get what that value

00:15:23.159 --> 00:15:24.159
actually is.

00:15:24.159 --> 00:15:29.080
And when I got this to work, and it's just pretty much arithmetic behind the scenes,

00:15:29.080 --> 00:15:30.320
it really was nice.

00:15:30.320 --> 00:15:35.280
Or you can add these together within a function call.

00:15:35.280 --> 00:15:36.280
Okay.

00:15:36.280 --> 00:15:38.559
So let's do some harder arithmetic.

00:15:38.719 --> 00:15:46.000
So we can compare the DebKeeper method with the method from the third edition of the Encyclopedia

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:47.960
Britannica from 1797.

00:15:47.960 --> 00:15:53.099
So this is how they actually talked about doing arithmetic.

00:15:53.099 --> 00:15:57.880
So this is in the arithmetic article.

00:15:57.880 --> 00:16:07.440
So here you can see on the left a fairly complex way in which they multiply 15 pounds, 3 shillings,

00:16:07.440 --> 00:16:09.359
and 8 pence by 32.

00:16:09.359 --> 00:16:14.679
They break it down into 8, multiply it by 8, and then multiply it by 4.

00:16:14.679 --> 00:16:22.960
And they're doing, they're carrying over the units sort of behind the scenes.

00:16:22.960 --> 00:16:25.119
Division is even harder.

00:16:25.119 --> 00:16:30.280
So I'm going to concentrate on, there's two examples here, but the example on the right

00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:33.200
is, and here we get to different bases.

00:16:33.200 --> 00:16:35.919
So this is a weight.

00:16:35.919 --> 00:16:44.119
So it's dividing 345 hundredweight, 1 quarter, and 8 pounds by 22.

00:16:44.119 --> 00:16:50.200
And if you try and figure out what they're doing here, it's really confusing.

00:16:50.200 --> 00:16:56.919
And they have little dots to figure out where they are, but it's not helpful.

00:16:56.919 --> 00:17:00.119
And so we have to change our bases.

00:17:00.119 --> 00:17:09.040
And so that's what you see there at the bottom of the third line there, is that the bases

00:17:09.040 --> 00:17:16.439
are, so a quarter weight is, there's 4 in a hundredweight, and there's 28 pounds in

00:17:16.439 --> 00:17:19.000
a quarter.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:24.079
I didn't know this either before I looked at this.

00:17:24.400 --> 00:17:32.640
Okay, so it's nice that we get to not have to do all this, like fifth grade math.

00:17:32.640 --> 00:17:36.280
I mean, I never knew that fifth grade math would be so important.

00:17:36.280 --> 00:17:42.920
But what about larger account books?

00:17:42.920 --> 00:17:48.680
So this is a picture of the person whose account book I've worked on the most, and the account

00:17:48.680 --> 00:17:49.680
book itself.

00:17:50.239 --> 00:17:54.959
Jan Delafayette de Oude, or the Elder.

00:17:54.959 --> 00:18:03.680
So his account book, if you look at the inside, it looks like this.

00:18:03.680 --> 00:18:10.160
And it's about 300 pages, and then there's two of them.

00:18:10.160 --> 00:18:17.479
They cover the period from his death on November 8, 1582, until the end of December, 1594.

00:18:17.920 --> 00:18:28.079
Even then, the heirs hadn't received all their inheritance, and in fact, the heirs continued

00:18:28.079 --> 00:18:35.520
to argue over the inheritance until basically they died in the 1610s, and then their children

00:18:35.520 --> 00:18:41.780
also continued to argue over it.

00:18:41.780 --> 00:18:46.239
So what I want to do, I don't have much time, but I just want to show some, instead of showing

00:18:46.239 --> 00:18:48.680
the code to do this, show some visualizations.

00:18:48.680 --> 00:18:54.319
So basically, this is things that I couldn't do because I wouldn't want to put all this

00:18:54.319 --> 00:19:00.680
data into a spreadsheet because I didn't know how to do anything with it, and now I can.

00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:12.920
So here you have an overview of the beginning of the estate, when he passed away.

00:19:12.920 --> 00:19:22.040
In the red circles show the accounts that are in debt to the estate, and the blue in

00:19:22.040 --> 00:19:23.160
credit to the estate.

00:19:23.160 --> 00:19:31.400
And so the biggest blue shows basically the amount that Jan de Aude's assets were greater

00:19:31.400 --> 00:19:39.040
than his liabilities, 41,112 pounds, 10 shillings, 5 pence.

00:19:39.040 --> 00:19:44.959
And remember, the pence mattered because they had to be equally divided.

00:19:44.959 --> 00:19:54.640
Here you just have a little line chart showing how and when the nine heirs received their

00:19:54.640 --> 00:19:57.280
inheritance.

00:19:57.280 --> 00:20:04.199
This is my version of a financial chart, but it goes over many years.

00:20:04.199 --> 00:20:10.599
You see that before his death, he owed his children money because he owed his children

00:20:10.599 --> 00:20:14.280
money for their maternal inheritance, which makes things even worse.

00:20:14.280 --> 00:20:22.880
Then there's a long gap because of the problems that they had, and then at the end, you still

00:20:22.880 --> 00:20:30.920
see nothing that they didn't become even.

00:20:30.920 --> 00:20:36.040
So just one last thing just to show what's possible.

00:20:36.040 --> 00:20:43.439
This is a network graph, again, showing the accounts and how they're related to each other.

00:20:43.439 --> 00:20:48.479
So this has obviously gotten me a long way from where I started, but basically I was

00:20:48.479 --> 00:20:56.319
able to get here because of the skills that I gained by looking into the Tidyverse, and

00:20:56.319 --> 00:21:00.000
that's pretty much what I used in the package.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:07.520
So thank you for listening, and thank you for having such a great conference.

